<exercises xml:id="ex-ArcLengthSurfaceArea">
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The formula for arc length of the function <m>f(x)</m> on the interval <m>[a,b]</m> is <m> \displaystyle L = \int_{x=a}^{x=b} \sqrt{1+f'(x)^2}\;dx</m>. Explain how this definition is built, using the slice-and-sum method. Make sure to explain how we the Pythagorean Theorem is involved.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Why do we use <m>f'(x)</m> in the formula for arc length?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following curves on intervals, evaluate the arc length.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y = -6x+2 </m> on <m>[1,5]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y=\dfrac{x^{3/2}}{3}</m> on <m>[0,60]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y=\dfrac{x^4}{4}+ \dfrac{1}{8x^2}</m> on <m>[1,3]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following curves on intervals, set up an integral representing the arc length. Do not evaluate.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   <m>y=\tan^2(x)</m> on <m>\left[-\frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{4}\right]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   <m>y=\ln(x^2)</m> on <m>[1, e]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   <m>y = \sqrt{x+1}</m> on <m>[-1,8]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Why is the formula for arc length seemingly involved in the integral formula for surface area of a solid of revolution?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In the integral formula <m>A = \dint_a^b 2\pi f(x) \sqrt{1+f'(x)^2} \; dx</m>, what does <m>f(x)</m> represent? What about <m>2\pi</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following curves and intervals, find the surface area of the solid formed when the curve is revolved around the <m>x</m>-axis.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y = 2x+3</m> on <m>[0,3]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y = 4\sqrt{x}</m> on <m>[4, 9]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y=\dfrac{x^4}{4}+ \dfrac{1}{8x^2}</m> on <m>[1,3]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following curves and intervals, set up the surface area of the solid formed when the curve is revolved around the <m>x</m>-axis. Do not evaluate the integral.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y = \sin\left(e^{x^2}\right)+1</m> on <m>[0,2]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>y = \ln(x^2)</m> on <m>[1,e]</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
</exercises>